1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,460
 I mentioned that JavaScript owns the document-object model.

2
00:00:03,460 --> 00:00:07,480
 The document-object model is what we see when we're looking at the browser.

3
00:00:07,480 --> 00:00:12,820
 A browser parses the HTML, sometimes our JavaScript writes it, and then creates this object we

4
00:00:12,820 --> 00:00:16,760
 call the document-object model, which is then displayed to the user through a window.

5
00:00:16,760 --> 00:00:20,600
 A window is the subset of the document-object model.

6
00:00:20,600 --> 00:00:25,360
 In whatever JavaScript we write, we can read, manipulate, and update the DOM.

7
00:00:25,360 --> 00:00:30,280
 And as soon as the DOM is updated, the user sees the updates through the window.

8
00:00:30,280 --> 00:00:35,320
 And we can also just go into the debugger and directly manipulate the document-object

9
00:00:35,320 --> 00:00:36,400
 model.

10
00:00:36,400 --> 00:00:40,580
 So if we go back to the 01 NoScript, there's no JavaScript in here.

11
00:00:40,580 --> 00:00:45,320
 So you just go, it shows you a header and a paragraph, and that's the document-object

12
00:00:45,320 --> 00:00:46,320
 model.

13
00:00:46,320 --> 00:00:51,480
 But you'll note that if you go into Inspect Element and then go into that paragraph tag,

14
00:00:51,480 --> 00:00:55,480
 you can change and add the word cool.

15
00:00:55,480 --> 00:01:00,680
 In a sense, the debugger is JavaScript, and you can actually type JavaScript commands into

16
00:01:00,680 --> 00:01:03,860
 the debugger if you do the right thing.

17
00:01:03,860 --> 00:01:08,520
 But the debugger is owning the document-object model as well.

18
00:01:08,520 --> 00:01:11,400
 And so you simply can change the document-object model.

19
00:01:11,400 --> 00:01:16,700
 And literally, it changes the UI, but truly the document-object model changes.

20
00:01:16,700 --> 00:01:20,180
 So you can even change the kind of a tag you're dealing with.

21
00:01:20,180 --> 00:01:21,800
 You could turn this into an anchor tag.

22
00:01:21,800 --> 00:01:23,440
 You could add some hrefs.

23
00:01:23,440 --> 00:01:26,440
 You can change the document-object model.

24
00:01:26,440 --> 00:01:31,000
 You're displayed-- it just-- you change it, and you see it.

25
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:33,920
 Now, I mentioned this thing called the window.

26
00:01:33,920 --> 00:01:38,500
 There are two sort of foundational objects in JavaScript in the browser.

27
00:01:38,500 --> 00:01:39,500
 There's the DOM.

28
00:01:39,500 --> 00:01:42,440
 And the DOM is an abstraction.

29
00:01:42,440 --> 00:01:45,480
 It is a structured hierarchy of tags.

30
00:01:45,480 --> 00:01:47,600
 We call them elements.

31
00:01:47,600 --> 00:01:50,260
 The window is how we see it.

32
00:01:50,260 --> 00:01:54,920
 So you can think of this picture that I've been showing you, parsing the response, running

33
00:01:54,920 --> 00:02:01,120
 some JavaScript, and tweaking the document-object model, and showing it to the user.

34
00:02:01,120 --> 00:02:05,040
 And if you change the document-object model, it's immediately updated.

35
00:02:05,040 --> 00:02:11,520
 On the left, that's kind of an oversimplification, because the way we actually view the document-object

36
00:02:11,520 --> 00:02:14,380
 model is through the window.

37
00:02:14,380 --> 00:02:20,320
 The window is what's on your screen, and probably the most easy way to demonstrate this is to

38
00:02:20,320 --> 00:02:24,920
 understand that the document-object model could be very large, and the window could

39
00:02:24,920 --> 00:02:26,360
 be very small.

40
00:02:26,360 --> 00:02:31,240
 And the document-object model doesn't change, and you can resize the window back and forth.

41
00:02:31,240 --> 00:02:33,540
 So sometimes you see scroll bars.

42
00:02:33,540 --> 00:02:38,080
 The scroll bar is not a notion in the document-object model.

43
00:02:38,080 --> 00:02:39,760
 It's a notion in the window.

44
00:02:39,760 --> 00:02:41,560
 The window has a certain height.

45
00:02:41,560 --> 00:02:47,560
 The document-object model may or may not completely fit in the window, and that has to do with

46
00:02:47,560 --> 00:02:50,400
 the window height and so scroll bars.

47
00:02:50,400 --> 00:02:57,280
 And so for example, if you look at 06height.html, all it does is puts out the header, puts out

48
00:02:57,280 --> 00:03:02,960
 the paragraph, and then prints out window height and window width, window.innerHeight

49
00:03:02,960 --> 00:03:05,900
 and window.innerWidth.

50
00:03:05,900 --> 00:03:11,440
 These are the height of the window, not the document-object model, but the window through

51
00:03:11,440 --> 00:03:13,000
 which we're viewing it.

52
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:19,600
 And so if you show this page with the debugger turned on with a really tiny window, it says

53
00:03:19,600 --> 00:03:21,360
 that the height is 116.

54
00:03:21,360 --> 00:03:25,080
 If you make the window bigger and hit reload, it says the height's 256.

55
00:03:25,080 --> 00:03:31,000
 So in JavaScript, we can ask questions about the window, and we can do things to the window.

56
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:34,080
 One thing we could do is we could scroll it up and down, and that's actually a common

57
00:03:34,080 --> 00:03:35,860
 thing to do in JavaScript.

58
00:03:35,860 --> 00:03:39,040
 If you have a big document-object model, and you've got a scroll window, and you want to

59
00:03:39,040 --> 00:03:44,640
 show the user a particular thing, like go to bottom, JavaScript can scroll the window

60
00:03:44,640 --> 00:03:48,320
 down to the bottom or up or down.

61
00:03:48,320 --> 00:03:50,400
 I don't get those right very well.

62
00:03:50,400 --> 00:03:53,620
 But we can control the window.

63
00:03:53,620 --> 00:03:57,600
 In this case, we're simply asking it how tall you are and how wide you are, but we can also

64
00:03:57,600 --> 00:03:59,760
 control it.

65
00:03:59,760 --> 00:04:06,560
 And so if we take a look now and we make 07scroll.htm, we can see that we have nine paragraphs

66
00:04:06,560 --> 00:04:07,560
 and a header.

67
00:04:07,560 --> 00:04:11,080
 That is the actual content.

68
00:04:11,080 --> 00:04:14,040
 And if we have a tall window, we can see the whole document.

69
00:04:14,040 --> 00:04:18,360
 But if we make the window smaller, then we can only see a subset of the document-object

70
00:04:18,360 --> 00:04:19,360
 model.

71
00:04:19,360 --> 00:04:23,240
 And so the window height changes, and if you look, you now have a scroll bar.

72
00:04:23,240 --> 00:04:24,400
 And what does the scroll bar do?

73
00:04:24,400 --> 00:04:28,440
 Well, it just takes and moves the document-object model up and down.

74
00:04:28,440 --> 00:04:32,960
 Well, it moves the part of the document-object, our view to the document-object model up and

75
00:04:32,960 --> 00:04:33,960
 down.

76
00:04:33,960 --> 00:04:38,320
 And if you're doing an inspect element in some browsers, you will see that it's telling

77
00:04:38,320 --> 00:04:44,480
 us with little kind of annotations that the body is being scrolled right now, and up through

78
00:04:44,480 --> 00:04:50,920
 paragraph four is overflowed off the screen up, and paragraph seven, eight, and nine have

79
00:04:50,920 --> 00:04:53,240
 overflowed and they've gone off the screen below.

80
00:04:53,240 --> 00:04:57,680
 Now if you play with this and you resize it and refresh it and resize it and refresh it,

81
00:04:57,680 --> 00:05:03,000
 you'll see this whole-- I mean, on the left, the whole thing shows, and so body is not indicated

82
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:09,080
 as the scrollable element, and the headers not overflow, et cetera.

83
00:05:09,080 --> 00:05:12,720
 So you can play with this, but play with it with different sizes, refresh it, and then

84
00:05:12,720 --> 00:05:17,880
 inspect element, and watch how the scroll, the overflow, and the scroll bar-- and in

85
00:05:17,880 --> 00:05:21,360
 this case, I'm not printing out height, but you would be seeing that the height would

86
00:05:21,360 --> 00:05:23,760
 actually change.

87
00:05:23,760 --> 00:05:28,040
 So one of the things that we're going to do next is we're going to modify the document-object

88
00:05:28,040 --> 00:05:37,560
 model in JavaScript.

